rer to prove his innocence; Dexter Filkins (The New Yorker) on the emotional effort by an Iraq War veteran to make amends for the role he played in the deaths of innocent Iraqis; Chris Jones (Esquire) on Robert A. Caro's epic, ongoing investigation into the life and work of Lyndon Johnson; Charles C. Mann (Orion) on the odds of human beings' survival as a species; and Roger Angell (The New Yorker) on aging, dying, and loss. The former infantryman Brian Mockenhaupt (Byliner) describes modern combat in Afghanistan and its ability both to forge and challenge friendships; Ta-Nehisi Coates (The Atlantic) reflects on the complex racial terrain traversed by Barack Obama; Frank Rich (New York) assesses Mitt Romney's ambiguous candidacy; and Dahlia Lithwick (Slate) looks at the current and future implications of an eventful year in Supreme Court history. The volume also includes an interview on the art of screenwriting with Terry Southern from The Paris Review and an award-winning short story by Stephen King published in Harper's magazine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAmerican prose literaturey21st century. 0aJournalismxAwardszUnited States. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Essays.2bisacsh1 aAngell, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBennet, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoates, Ta-Nehisi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColloff, Pamela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEditors, The American Society of Magazine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aErdely, Sabrina Rubin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFilkins, Dexter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraeber, Charles, econtr